<gtr:projectOverview xmlns:gtr="http://gtr.ukri.org/api"><gtr:projectComposition><gtr:collaborations/><gtr:leadResearchOrganisation url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/3A5E126D-C175-4730-9B7B-E6D8CF447F83"><gtr:id>3A5E126D-C175-4730-9B7B-E6D8CF447F83</gtr:id><gtr:name>University College London</gtr:name><gtr:department>Institute of Cognitive Neuroscience</gtr:department><gtr:address><gtr:line1>Gower Street</gtr:line1><gtr:line4>London</gtr:line4><gtr:postCode>WC1E 6BT</gtr:postCode><gtr:region>London</gtr:region><gtr:country>United Kingdom</gtr:country></gtr:address><gtr:typeInd>RO</gtr:typeInd></gtr:leadResearchOrganisation><gtr:organisationRoles><gtr:organisationRole url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/3A5E126D-C175-4730-9B7B-E6D8CF447F83"><gtr:id>3A5E126D-C175-4730-9B7B-E6D8CF447F83</gtr:id><gtr:name>University College London</gtr:name><gtr:address><gtr:line1>Gower Street</gtr:line1><gtr:line4>London</gtr:line4><gtr:postCode>WC1E 6BT</gtr:postCode><gtr:region>London</gtr:region><gtr:country>United Kingdom</gtr:country></gtr:address><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>LEAD_RO</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:organisationRole></gtr:organisationRoles><gtr:personRoles><gtr:personRole url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/C545C409-C7A7-4154-8D74-CC051D05B598"><gtr:id>C545C409-C7A7-4154-8D74-CC051D05B598</gtr:id><gtr:firstName>Martha</gtr:firstName><gtr:surname>Turner</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>RESEARCHER</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=PTA-037-27-0085"><gtr:id>23667A18-4A50-4664-BE04-E14BEF35B6CE</gtr:id><gtr:title>Executive Control Processes in Confabulation and Delusions</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>PTA-037-27-0085</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>Delusional false beliefs such as those involved in confabulation and schizophrenia affect as many as 1-2 per cent of the population, and are a significant social and healthcare problem, yet are poorly understood. Different types of false belief have historically been treated separately, however they may share common mechanisms.&lt;/p> 
&lt;p>The proposed project aims to apply cutting edge theoretical and experimental work emerging from three research programmes at UCL (including Dr Turner?s own) to provide the first model of delusion formation across aetiologies, in terms of breakdowns in a range of production, monitoring and executive processes associated with the prefrontal cortex. Specifically, it investigates the possibility that dysfunction of the inferior and medial regions of the prefrontal cortex may lead to difficulty in distinguishing internal from external events, and in monitoring our own beliefs.&lt;/p> 
&lt;p>The project will investigate impairments in ?descriptor? (data gathering, strategic recall and cue use), ?editor? (monitoring, self correction and response suppression) and ?mediator? (reality monitoring, plausibility judgement and cognitive estimation) processes using both functional brain imaging and behavioural approaches. The aims of the project are to identify the critical brain regions and cognitive processes involved in false beliefs regardless of aetiology, hence leading to recommendations for rehabilitation and management of these phenomena.&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2008-09-30</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2006-10-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>71789</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication><gtr:id>2C5CEEDC-FC8F-4FD5-AE61-BBC6C0D0A326</gtr:id><gtr:title>Confabulation: damage to a specific inferior medial prefrontal system.</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>Cortex; a journal devoted to the study of the nervous system and behavior</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/8daeffc6ecb74edc3c7865ba05e44d35"><gtr:id>8daeffc6ecb74edc3c7865ba05e44d35</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Turner MS</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2008-01-01</gtr:date><gtr:issn>0010-9452</gtr:issn><gtr:outcomeId>pm_53cbf80bf80828bcc</gtr:outcome